Step 1: Connect to EC2

Since you already have EC2:

ssh -i your-key.pem ec2-user@your-public-ip

Step 2: Install Docker

Run:

sudo yum update -y

sudo yum install docker -y

sudo service docker start

sudo usermod -aG docker ec2-user

Now logout and reconnect:

exit

Reconnect again:

ssh -i your-key.pem ec2-user@your-public-ip

Check Docker:

docker --version

You should see version.

Step 3: Create project folder

mkdir mywebserver

cd mywebserver

Step 4: Create simple HTML page

Create file:

nano index.html

Paste:

<html>

<head>

<title>My First Docker Web Server</title>

</head>

<body>

<h1>Hello from Docker on AWS EC2</h1>

</body>

</html>

Save:

CTRL + O

ENTER

CTRL + X

Step 5: Create Dockerfile

Now create Dockerfile:

nano Dockerfile

Paste:

FROM nginx:latest

COPY index.html /usr/share/nginx/html/index.html

Save again.

Explanation line by line

Line 1

FROM nginx:latest

Means:

Start from existing nginx image

Nginx = web server software

NGINX is already available in Docker Hub.

So Docker downloads ready-made nginx.

Line 2

COPY index.html /usr/share/nginx/html/index.html

Means:

Copy your webpage into nginx web folder.

That folder is where nginx serves files from.

Why only 2 lines?

Because nginx already contains:

Linux

Web server installed

Port configured

You only add your page.

That is Docker power

Step 6: Build Docker image

Run:

docker build -t myweb:v1 .

Explanation:

docker build

Build image

-t

Tag name

myweb:v1

Image name = myweb

Version = v1

Current folder

You should see:

Successfully built

Step 7: Check image

docker images

You will see:

myweb v1

Step 8: Run container

docker run -d -p 80:80 myweb:v1

Explanation:

-d

Run in background

-p 80:80

Map:

EC2 port 80 → container port 80

Step 9: Check running container

docker ps

You should see running container.

Step 10: Open browser

Go:

http://your-ec2-public-ip

You will see:

Hello from Docker on AWS EC2

If webpage does NOT open

Check EC2 security group:

Allow:

HTTP 80

Important.

